Introduction

Any analysis of association between genotype and phenotype starts with the collection of good phenotypic data and adequate statistical analysis. Collecting good phenotypic data is not just about being careful when measuring a certain trait either in the field or in the laboratory, but it also involves good experimental practices. Therefore, whenever possible, well-designed experiments including repetitions, casualization and local control (if necessary); should be prioritized. Such aspects will certainly affect downstream results associated to GWAS analyses. In this short tutorial we will consider different experimental analyses, using different approaches.

We will follow the general structure:

  • We will consider a case of study (real data in blueberry)
  • Run simple descriptive analyses
  • Generate some genotypic metrics
  • Check the possibility to use post-hoc analysis for the blueberry example
  • General idea about experimental desing

Important R packages:

  • dplyr: data wrangling
  • ggplot: data visualisation
  • asreml-R: fitting mixed models

Statistical Model

Modelling Process

  1. Understand the problem
  2. Plan and collect the data
  3. Explore the data (data visualization)
  4. Postulate a model
  5. Fit a model (least square, ML, REML, Bayesian)
  6. Check the model (residuals, prediction, goodness-of-fit)
  7. Go back to iv and try again
  8. Use the model

Fixed vs.Â Random Effects

Herein, we will consider different ways to model the genotypic effects. This discussion will start under the basis of a central equation in quantitative genetics where Phenotype = Genotype + Environment or just P=G+E. From here, we will focus on the G portion by constructing expressions that predict/estimate the genotypic value of the genotypes in the population. Simply stating, our central objective is to bring to GWAS analyses âcorrected phenotypic valuesâ, in which eventual associations with molecular markers have genetic causes and is not biased for eventual noises caused by environmental factors.

We will show four different metrics that can be computed and how (and why) they are more or less correlated. This discussion also involves definitions about fixed and random effects. Sometimes, the decision as to whether certain effects are fixed or random is not immediately obvious. In this class (Linear Mixel Model), I present more details about this topic. Below, there is a simple table constrasting fixed and random effects.

Fixed Random
Objectives compare specific levels of a certain factor conclusions draw for a larger universe of interest
Sampling treatment levels are selected by the investigator treatment levels are randomly sampled
Statistically hypothesis tests on the mean \(H_0: \tau_1 = \tau_2 = ...= \tau_n\) hypothesis tests on the variance component \(H_0: \sigma^2_{\tau} = 0\)
Number of observation any Rule of thumb: >5-10

Genotypic Metrics

In this workshop, we will obtain four metrics associated to the âgenotypic effectâ.

  • Raw mean
  • BLUEs (when genotype effect is fixed)
  • BLUPs (when genotype effect is random indexed by an Identity variance and covariance matrix)
  • A-BLUPs (when genotype effect is random indexed by a pedigree)
# Statistical model 
# y = m + year + tree + e

library(asreml)

# Raw Mean across both years
firm.mean = firmness %>% 
  group_by(tree)%>% 
  summarise_if(is.numeric, mean, na.rm=T) %>% 
  select(tree, firm) %>% 
  mutate_if(is.numeric, ~ifelse(is.nan(.), NA, .)) %>% 
  as.data.frame

# BLUEs 
fm1 = asreml(fixed=firm ~ year + tree, data=firmness)
blues = predict(fm1, classify = "tree",pworkspace="10gb")

# BLUPs (identity matrix)
fm2 = asreml(fixed=firm ~ year,
             random = ~ tree, data=firmness)
blups = predict(fm2, classify = "tree",pworkspace="10gb")

# BLUPs (Amatrix)
ped = openxlsx::read.xlsx("/home/lferrao/Dropbox (UFL)//PosDoc_UF_NewGenome/DataSet/Pedigree/PedigreeV59.xlsx",sheet=1)[,1:3]
A = AGHmatrix::Amatrix(ped)
Afirm = A[as.character(unique(firmness$tree)),as.character(unique(firmness$tree))]
fm3 = asreml(fixed=firm ~ year,
             random = ~ vm(tree,Afirm), data=firmness)
A_blups = predict(fm3, classify = "tree",pworkspace="10gb")

# Combining all results
geno.metrics= data.frame(tree=firm.mean$tree,
  avg = firm.mean$firm,
  blue = blues$pvals$predicted.value,
  blups = blups$pvals$predicted.value)

geno.metrics = merge(geno.metrics,A_blups$pvals, by="tree") %>% 
  select(-std.error, -status) %>% 
  rename(A_blups = predicted.value)

save(geno.metrics, file="/home/lferrao/Dropbox (UFL)/classes/gwas_tutorial/1.Phenotypic/hands_on1/geno_metric.Rdata")

All the four metrics were saved in a single data frame. We have the following questions:

load("/home/lferrao/Dropbox (UFL)/classes/gwas_tutorial/1.Phenotypic/hands_on1/geno_metric.Rdata")

Regarding the blue and the avg value, why values are not the same?

Values are not the same because the data is not balanced. When we have phenotypes collected in both years, blues and raw.avg will be the same (see the genotype 13.100.10, for example). But in the case of trees with phenotypic data collected in single year, blues will be able to correct the phenotypic effect for the year effect.

What is the correlation between the metrics?

library(GGally)
ggpairs(geno.metrics[,-1])

Observations

  • Correlation between avg, blues and blups are very strong, even with moderate imbalance in the data set.
  • In the case of missing data in both years, avg and blue will export NA data, while the blups will be able to predict a value for the missing value ( this value will be very similar to the general mean of both years, in this case that we have only the year effect in the model)
  • I have seen papers using all these 3 metrics for downstream analyses related to genomic selection and GWAS studies.
  • I would suggest to use the blues. To avoid double shrinkage of estimates
  • The A-blups is in fact the most different metric. There are a couple os reasons for that. The main one is that the genotypic metrics will suffer a shrinkage dictated not only by the heritability of the trait, but also by pedigree. Pedigree allows the model to borrow information across genotypes. It makes some genotypes more similar to others depending on the genealogical relationship between them (and the pedigree depth).
  • While pedigree blups is very beneficial for prediction purposes, some authors argue that it can cause bias in associative studies. For more details, check this study

Outputs from the Phenotypic Analyses

Step-by-step:

  • Fit an animal model per year and estimate genetic parameters
  • Plot diagnostic
  • Combine both years
  • Fit the blues per year and combined
# Year 1
y1 = firmness %>%  filter(year==2014) %>% droplevels()
mean(y1$firm,na.rm=T)
fm.y1 = asreml(fixed=firm ~ year, random = ~ vm(tree,Afirm), data=y1)
summary(fm.y1)$varcomp
vpredict(fm.y1,h2~V1/(V1+V2)) # 0.47
plot(fm.y1)

# Year 2
y2 = firmness %>%  filter(year==2015) %>% droplevels()
mean(y2$firm,na.rm=T)
fm.y2 = asreml(fixed=firm ~ year, random = ~ vm(tree,Afirm), data=y2)
summary(fm.y2)$varcomp
vpredict(fm.y2,h2~V1/(V1+V2)) #0.78
plot(fm.y2)

Unreplicated Trial and Spatial Analyses

In this topic we will deal with heterogeneity of errors in a post-hoc analysis, rather than in the experimental design. The use of spatial analyses can improve the estimation of genetic effects by modeling more accurately the spatial distribution of error effects in a field trial. Results can potentially improve downstream analyses related to genomic prediction and GWAS.

Below one example using the same data set, but using the size trait. Visually, is it possible to observe any phenotypic trends?

size = read.xlsx("/home/lferrao/Dropbox (UFL)/classes/gwas_tutorial/1.Phenotypic/hands_on1/blueberry_firmness.xlsx", sheet=2)
ggplot(size, aes(col,row, color = size)) + 
  geom_point(size=1.8)+
  scale_color_gradient(low = "white", high = "firebrick") +
  facet_wrap(~year,ncol=2)

StatgenSTA Package

  • The statgenSTA (Single Trial Analysis) package is developed as an easy-to-use package for analyzing data of plant breeding experiments with many options for plotting and reporting the results of the analyses. The package can be used for visualizing trial data, analyzing data per trial and automatically creating reports of the analysis.
  • Website
  • Method: SpATS package, which uses 2-dimensional smoothing with P-spline as described in this paper
  • Open source package.
  • We will fit the package for the firmness data

Model:

\[y_{ijk} = m + r_i + c_j + f(r,c)_{ij} + g_k + e_{ijk}\]

where:

  • \(f(r, c)\) is a smooth function of row (r) and column (c) plot coordinates representing the fitted spatial surface, which simultaneously accounts for global and local trends
  • \(g_k\) is the genotypic effect that can be considered as fixed or random. All random effects were assumed independent homoscedastic and normally distributed with zero mean.
library(statgenSTA)
# Fit a spatial model only for the year 1
y1 = firmness %>%  filter(year==2014) %>% droplevels()
dropsTD <- createTD(data = firmness,
                    genotype = "tree", 
                    year = "year",
                    rowCoord = "row", 
                    colCoord = "col")
summary(dropsTD, traits="firm")

Experimental Desing

Definitions

  • Treatment: description of the set of different experimental conditions to be tested
  • Experimental Unit: the smallest division of the experimental material such that any two units may receive different treatments in the actual experiment
  • Desing: is the allocation of treatments to the experimental units. A design is complete if each treatment appears the within each block and balanced if each treatment appears the same number of times.
  • Replication: important to estimate the experimental error
    • Technical replication: several measurements are taken from the same biological material. Technical replication is always a pseudo-replication.
    • Biological replication: when measurements are taken from several independent biological subjects.
  • Examples of asreml-R codes for fitting in this link from PCB6555
  • Other examples in this link

Some tips when fitting LMM in asreml-R

Convergence issues

  • Function: update(asreml_object) or increase the maxiter=20
  • Decrese the stepsize=0.01
  • Use initial values: init

Memory space

  • Try to increase the workspace="10gb", when fitting LMM using the asareml function
  • Increase the pworkspace="10gb" when using the predict function
  • Be carefull to check your system monitor to track your RAM memory
